description.plain: Creed is an American rock band, formed in 1993 in Tallahassee, Florida. The band’s original line-up consists of lead vocalist Scott Stapp, guitarist and vocalist Mark Tremonti, bassist Brian Marshall, and drummer Scott Phillips.

description.plain: “With Arms Wide Open” is the eighth track on Human Clay. Scott Stapp wrote this song when he found out he was going to be a father but did not know if he was ready for such a role just yet. But eventually he found the will to do what he was destined to do. To become a good father and show his child everything about the world, “with arms wide open”.

description.plain:
The title song of the album and the third track of My Own Prison talks about the consequences of one’s actions, and how they have to live with it for the rest of their lives.

My Own Prison is the song and album that led Creed to fame for years to come.

description.plain:
“What If” is the 2nd song on Creed’s 1999 hit album Human Clay. It is produced by John Kurzweg and written by Mark Tremonti and Scott Stapp. It was released along with the album on September 28, 1999, but then released as a single from the Scream 3 soundtrack later on January 31, 2000. The song’s lyrics talk about hatred and people who prey on others. It is one of Creed’s heaviest songs, and one of their only songs considered to be metal.

The song is featured in the 2000 thriller film Scream 3 as part of the soundtrack. The music video accompanying the song features the members of Creed being hunted down and killed by the Ghostface character from the Scream movies and features actor David Arquette.

The song was covered by Chris Daughtry on the fifth season of the show American Idol in 2006.

description.plain:
“Bullets” is the second single from Creed’s third album, Weathered. It is often regarded and known as the heaviest song by the band. This song is an almost complete departure from the post-grunge sound that was established with Creed’s first two albums.

The song was written during a very difficult the band as they were forced to kick bassist Brian Marshall from the band for comments he made on a radio show. Despite the speculated turmoil from fans, Stapp had stated in a later interview that Marshall left the band on his own wishes.

Unlike other songs, “Bullets” is very aggressive both lyrically and instrumentally, showing off a thick distorted sound with heavy palm muted guitar riffs and pounding double kick drums.

Surprisingly, the song has also received a high budget animated music video.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oPzhUp8mWgs
